From Teaneck Township:
The National Weather Center has issued a TROPICAL STORM WATCH, a TORNADO WATCH, and a FLASH FLOOD WATCH for our area today.

Anticipate tropical storm force winds 35-45 mph with gusts up to to 73 mph until early this evening resulting in downed trees, power outages, and flash flooding from heavy downpours.

Take down all temporary structures, including outdoor dining tents and umbrellas. Secure loose furniture and other objects. Charge your electronic devices now.

The situation is somewhat favorable for tornadoes. Stay within your shelter keeping informed of the latest tornado situation.

Remember, a tornado "warning" is issued when a tornado is imminent. Usually that means signs of an imminent tornado have been spotted on radar. Move quickly to the safest place within your shelter if a tornado warning is issued.

post_text:
Teaneck Apple Award Winners: Staff
After announcing our student winners on Friday, here are the staff members nominated and selected for having gone "above and beyond" during the pandemic...
Shema Stroud, Jenine Kea and Sheila Moore – and our partner, Kristen Appel of Maschios.
Whether sunny, raining, or even in some snow, these wonderful ladies showed up every day to make sure our families had food and even created care packages for those who were in great need. Each day, they helped to deliver a smile when smiling was in short supply! Thank you to these wonderful staff members and our partners at Maschios!

post_text:
The Teaneck Apple Award Winners!
Recently, our Board of Education recognized those who were nominated by our Teaneck community and selected by District Leadership for having gone “above and beyond” to serve our community and our students during this pandemic.
Today, we are proudly sharing our student winners:
1.) Liam Engler, Bryant/kindergarten - for creating the KinderAcademy on YouTube to teach lessons to his fellow classmates
2.) Carson Myers, Bryant prek classroom, for his extra hardwork and effort during the pandemic...he is 3 years old and his teacher wrote in to tell us about him
3.) William Cross Charles, Lowell/3rd Grade - for his YouTube show "The Will to Read", which helped develop his public speaking skills while helping out his fellow students with his videos
4.) Niah Aldave and Reem Abouganba 7th graders at Thomas Jefferson Middle School - they worked together to form Nemo School of Online Classes to help each other and fellow classmates navigate the daily classwork in the absence of teachers.
Congratulations to these bright young minds! 👏👏👏

post_text: Ava Weinstein, one of our 5th grade students at Thomas Jefferson Middle School, has won Artsonia's 4th-6th "ARTIST OF THE WEEK" (Ava32393) for May 24 - May 30. Her artwork, which received over one thousand votes, is currently featured on Artsonia (www.artsonia.com)an online art portfolio platform that is utilized by Art educators in our district and across the nation. Special thanks to Ms. Brittany Eisele for her tireless efforts to bring out the best in our students!

CATEGORY: Future Broadcaster
William Cross Charles attends Lowell Elementary School where Ms. Maikisch is his 3rd grade teacher. William has been working extremely hard since the Learning from Home began.
With the help of Mom, they decided to create a video to help motivate him in his public speaking. To his surprise, he not only had an amazing time making the video but he is already thinking about what he can work on next.
The name of Williams’s show is called "The Will to Read".
Everyone they have shared it with is excited for the next one...we could not agree more! Plus we LOVE his enthusiasm!

https://youtu.be/9jKTu2C8vcg

CATEGORY: Awesome!
Liam Engler from Ms. La-Mui's kindergarten class at Bryant has partnered with his Dad to create the KinderAcademy! Liam's YouTube lessons are designed to help his friends with their home assignments. Dad helps with the filming and editing, but Liam directs exactly what he wants to do and how he wants it to look. He is also very adamant about putting out a new video every day so everyone can keep learning even though they're not in school. Here's one on his lessons on the weather:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iiH_hxeIdn8

post_text:
Attention Parents/Guardians:
Our Superintendent has sent important emails to your home around 5 pm yesterday and 11 am today. Please check your emails!

Another email will be forthcoming tomorrow for our Special Education families.

If you are not receiving these emails, please contact your child’s school tomorrow before 2 pm on Monday. The principals will be in the school buildings. Families without internet access can receive home packets during 11 am - 1 pm on Monday. No one will be able to enter the school buildings beyond this time.

Lesson plans are available on our website here: www.teaneckschools.org Click on the STUDENT tab....it’s also available from the PARENT tab.

Thank you for your patience and cooperation.
